# maybe-this-one

A dumb little password auditing tool written in Zig.

It takes a hash, grabs a giant list of possible passwords, and repeatedly says:

> maybe this one

until something works.

Or it doesn't.

Either way, at least it tried.

## What it does

* Reads a target hash
* Loads a wordlist
* Hashes every candidate
* Compares them
* Repeats the process very, very quickly
* Uses multiple CPU cores because waiting is boring

## Why?

Because sometimes you have a password hash and a suspicious amount of free time.


## Features

* ⚡ Avrage Fast
* 📦 Tiny executable
* 🔧 NO dependencies

## Supported algorithms

* MD5
* SHA-1
* SHA-256
* SHA-512
* Blake-3

More may be added later.

## Build

Requirements:

* Zig 0.16+

```bash
git clone https://github.com/yourname/maybe-this-one

cd maybe-this-one

zig build -Doptimize=ReleaseFast
```

## Usage

```bash
maybe-this-one -a sha256 -h <hash> -w passwords.txt
```

Example output:

```text
[1/1000000]

password
nope

123456
nope

qwerty
nope

password123
🎉 maybe this one

FOUND: password123
```

## Philosophy

Computers are really good at trying lots of things.

This program simply weaponizes optimism.

## Legal

Only use this against systems, files, or hashes you own or have permission to audit.

Do not be weird.

Be weird on yer own risk .

